4) For each group (cmdb_id,kpi_name) compute: in_window_count (already available), anomaly_count (number of rows marked high-or-low), earliest_anom_ts (earliest timestamp of any anomaly in window), max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window, max_high_deviation = max((value - p95)/p95) over high-anomaly rows (use absolute difference if p95==0), max_low_deviation = max((p5 - value)/p5) over low-anomaly rows (handle p5==0 similarly).
5) Return two compact tables (limit 20 rows each):
   a) Top 20 groups with anomaly_count > 0 sorted by earliest_anom_ts ascending (columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, anomaly_count, earliest_anom_ts, in_window_count, max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window, max_high_deviation, max_low_deviation).
   b) Top 20 groups with anomaly_count > 0 sorted by max(max_high_deviation, max_low_deviation) descending (same columns).

Also return the total number of groups that had anomaly_count > 0 (single scalar). Keep outputs compact and store the full anomaly-marked in-window table in a kernel variable for the next step.
